<subSubSection pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="60.[151,1436,1801,2007]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
The representatives of this tribe are characterized as follows (
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[837,1035,1801,1827]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara 2002b</bibRefCitation>
): head with lateral sutures subparallel and connected with antennal furrows (
<figureCitation box="[622,692,1837,1863]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1614,1638]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,918,1586]" captionTargetId="figure-342@37.[151,1436,918,1590]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 1. Key to tribes and genera 1" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876495" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876495/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
: 1aa); tarsal claws short (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[1040,1141,1837,1864]" captionStart="FIGURE 35" captionStartId="124.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-26@124.[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="124" captionText="FIGURE 35. Onycholyda kumamotonis, female, Japan – (a) dorsally, (b) lateroventrally, (c) head &amp; thorax dorsally, (d) head &amp; thorax ventrolaterally, (e) face, (f) antenna, (g) sawsheath laterally, (h) claw." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876576" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876576/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Figs 35h</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1153,1198,1837,1863]" captionStart="FIGURE 46" captionStartId="135.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-19@135.[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="135" captionText="FIGURE 46. Onycholyda yezoensis, female, Japan – (a) dorsally, (b) lateroventrally, (c) head &amp; thorax dorsally, (d) head &amp; thorax ventrolaterally, (e) face, (f) malar space setae, (g) sawsheath laterally, (h) claw, (i) antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876612" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876612/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">46h</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1211,1255,1837,1864]" captionStart="FIGURE 58" captionStartId="147.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-19@147.[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="147" captionText="FIGURE 58. Pamphilius aucupariae, female, Korea – (a) dorsally, (b) lateroventrally, (c) head &amp; thorax dorsally, (d) head &amp; thorax ventrolaterally, (e) face, (f) antenna, (g) claw, (h) sawsheath laterally." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876646" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876646/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<quantity box="[1211,1255,1837,1864]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="5.8" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="g" value="58.0">58g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1268,1314,1837,1863]" captionStart="FIGURE 87" captionStartId="176.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetId="figure-26@176.[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="176" captionText="FIGURE 87. Pamphilius itoi, female, Japan – (a) dorsally, (b) lateroventrally, (c) head &amp; thorax dorsally, (d) head &amp; thorax ventrolaterally, (e) face, (f) antenna, (g) sawsheath laterally, (h) claw." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876713" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876713/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">87h</figureCitation>
); forewing with vein Scl present (
<figureCitation box="[404,473,1873,1899]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1614,1638]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,918,1586]" captionTargetId="figure-342@37.[151,1436,918,1590]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 1. Key to tribes and genera 1" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876495" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876495/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
: 1bb); abdominal sternum 
<quantity box="[776,819,1873,1900]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.778" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="in" value="7.0">7 in</quantity>
female rather simply subconically swollen posteriorly, without paired ridges and triangular marginal depression (fig. 4K–M in 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[942,1134,1909,1935]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara 2002b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Takeuchi" authorityYear="1938" box="[1144,1279,1909,1935]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1144,1279,1909,1935]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Onycholyda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exceptionally has paired rounded ridges and a very flat (in ventral view) subtriangular marginal depression or weakly sclerotized posterior margin, fig. 4H–J in 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[491,685,1981,2007]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara 2002b</bibRefCitation>
); lancet with lamnium small (
<figureCitation box="[1018,1087,1981,2007]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1614,1638]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,918,1586]" captionTargetId="figure-342@37.[151,1436,918,1590]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 1. Key to tribes and genera 1" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876495" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876495/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
: 1cc).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="61.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
The tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1890" box="[310,441,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pamphiliini">Pamphiliini</taxonomicName>
is regarded as monophyletic. The characters listed above, except for the presence of the vein Sc 
<quantity box="[239,279,187,213]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
the forewing, are postulated as its autapomorphies. Our molecular analyses using COI and NaK genes also supported the monophyly of this tribe with UFBoot support of 100% (
<figureCitation box="[988,1118,222,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="97.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[294,1293,186,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@97.[279,1307,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="97" captionText="FIGURES 14–16: 14. Hypothesized relationships based on adult morphology in Pamphiliinae for several genera and species groups of Pamphilius (modified from Shinohara 2002b, only genera and species groups with molecular data are included). 15. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences. 16. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876530" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876530/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Figs 15, 16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="61.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
This tribe comprises five genera and 170 species in the recent world fauna (
<bibRefCitation author="Taeger, A. &amp; Blank, S. M. &amp; Liston, A. D." box="[1067,1280,259,285]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" pagination="1 - 1064" refId="ref80219" refString="Taeger, A., Blank, S. M. &amp; Liston, A. D. (2010) World catalog of Symphyta (Hymenoptera). Zootaxa, 2580 (1), 1 - 1064. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2580.1.1" type="journal article" year="2010">
Taeger 
<emphasis box="[1153,1211,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">et al.</emphasis>
2010
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Wei, M. - C." pageId="61" pageNumber="62" pagination="53 - 74" refId="ref79164" refString="Shinohara, A. &amp; Wei, M. - C. (2012) Pamphiliid sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) of Mt. Yunshan, Hunan Province, China. Memoirs of the National Museum of Nature and Science, Tokyo, 48, 53 - 74." type="journal article" year="2012">Shinohara &amp; Wei 2012</bibRefCitation>
, 2016; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Kiyoshi, T. &amp; Wei, M. - C. &amp; Kameda, Y." box="[348,607,295,321]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" pagination="75 - 81" refId="ref78172" refString="Shinohara, A., Kiyoshi, T., Wei, M. - C. &amp; Kameda, Y. (2018 c) Identification of larvae and recognition of new synonymy for two Chinese Onycholyda sawflies (Insecta: Hymenoptera: Pamphiliidae) based on molecular data. Species Diversity, 23, 75 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.12782 / specdiv. 23.75" type="journal article" year="2018">
Shinohara 
<emphasis box="[469,527,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">et al.</emphasis>
2018c
</bibRefCitation>
; present work). Here we treat three genera, 
<emphasis box="[1108,1237,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Chrysolyda</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Takeuchi" authorityYear="1938" box="[1252,1387,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1252,1387,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Onycholyda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1803" box="[151,279,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,279,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Pamphilius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, containing 52 species as occurring in the Russian Far East and 
<collectingCountry box="[996,1068,331,357]" name="South Korea" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Korea</collectingCountry>
. Of the three genera, 
<emphasis box="[1307,1436,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Chrysolyda</emphasis>
with only two world species and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Takeuchi" authorityYear="1938" box="[525,660,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[525,660,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Onycholyda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 42 world species were considered monophyletic based on morphology (
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[257,454,403,429]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara 2002b</bibRefCitation>
). Our molecular analyses using the COI and NaK sequences also strongly supported the monophyly of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Takeuchi" authorityYear="1938" box="[315,450,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[315,450,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Onycholyda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with UFBoot support of 100% (
<figureCitation box="[809,938,438,465]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="97.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[294,1293,186,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@97.[279,1307,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="97" captionText="FIGURES 14–16: 14. Hypothesized relationships based on adult morphology in Pamphiliinae for several genera and species groups of Pamphilius (modified from Shinohara 2002b, only genera and species groups with molecular data are included). 15. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences. 16. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876530" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876530/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Figs 15, 16</figureCitation>
). Molecular data for 
<emphasis box="[1171,1300,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Chrysolyda</emphasis>
and the two western Palaearctic genera, 
<taxonomicName authority="Konow, 1897" authorityName="Konow" authorityYear="1897" box="[463,753,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Kelidoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[463,597,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Kelidoptera</emphasis>
Konow, 1897
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Zirngiebl, 1937" authorityName="Zirngiebl" authorityYear="1937" box="[807,1182,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pseudocephaleia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[807,998,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Pseudocephaleia</emphasis>
Zirngiebl, 1937
</taxonomicName>
, were not available for the present study.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="61.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
The monophyly or non-monophyly of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1803" box="[634,762,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[634,762,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Pamphilius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its relationship with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Takeuchi" authorityYear="1938" box="[1048,1183,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1048,1183,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Onycholyda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be clarified by further studies. Working on morphological characters, 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[755,963,583,609]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara (2002b)</bibRefCitation>
was not able to detect any autapomorphies for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1803" box="[193,321,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[193,321,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Pamphilius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Takeuchi" authorityYear="1938" box="[387,522,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[387,522,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Onycholyda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was retrieved as a sister group of all 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1803" box="[962,1090,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[962,1090,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Pamphilius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stephens" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[1224,1357,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sylvarum">
<emphasis box="[1224,1357,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">P. sylvarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basilaris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">P. basilaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
groups in his cladogram (fig. 
<quantity box="[590,646,655,681]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.794" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" unit="in" value="11.0">11 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[653,848,655,681]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara 2002b</bibRefCitation>
; see 
<figureCitation box="[903,982,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="97.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[294,1293,186,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@97.[279,1307,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="97" captionText="FIGURES 14–16: 14. Hypothesized relationships based on adult morphology in Pamphiliinae for several genera and species groups of Pamphilius (modified from Shinohara 2002b, only genera and species groups with molecular data are included). 15. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences. 16. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876530" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876530/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
for an abbreviated version). In our NaK analysis, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1803" box="[256,384,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[256,384,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Pamphilius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was recovered as monophyletic with UFBoot support of 99% and sister to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Takeuchi" authorityYear="1938" box="[1239,1374,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1239,1374,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Onycholyda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="97.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[294,1293,186,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@97.[279,1307,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="97" captionText="FIGURES 14–16: 14. Hypothesized relationships based on adult morphology in Pamphiliinae for several genera and species groups of Pamphilius (modified from Shinohara 2002b, only genera and species groups with molecular data are included). 15. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences. 16. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876530" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876530/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
). In the COI analysis, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1803" box="[434,562,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[434,562,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Pamphilius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was retrieved as paraphyletic and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Takeuchi" authorityYear="1938" box="[950,1085,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[950,1085,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Onycholyda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was a part of large assemblage of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1803" box="[182,310,763,789]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[182,310,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Pamphilius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(supported by 97% UFBoot value) forming a sister group of 
<taxonomicName box="[1004,1141,763,788]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonicus">
<emphasis box="[1004,1141,763,788]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">P. japonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(currently belonging to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sylvaticus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">P. sylvaticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group) (
<figureCitation box="[363,449,798,825]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="97.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[294,1293,186,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@97.[279,1307,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="97" captionText="FIGURES 14–16: 14. Hypothesized relationships based on adult morphology in Pamphiliinae for several genera and species groups of Pamphilius (modified from Shinohara 2002b, only genera and species groups with molecular data are included). 15. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences. 16. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876530" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876530/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Therefore, the three available datasets, namely, morphology (
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[1174,1378,799,825]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara, 2002b</bibRefCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="97.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[294,1293,186,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@97.[279,1307,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="97" captionText="FIGURES 14–16: 14. Hypothesized relationships based on adult morphology in Pamphiliinae for several genera and species groups of Pamphilius (modified from Shinohara 2002b, only genera and species groups with molecular data are included). 15. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences. 16. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876530" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876530/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
), COI genes (present work, 
<figureCitation box="[496,576,834,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="97.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[294,1293,186,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@97.[279,1307,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="97" captionText="FIGURES 14–16: 14. Hypothesized relationships based on adult morphology in Pamphiliinae for several genera and species groups of Pamphilius (modified from Shinohara 2002b, only genera and species groups with molecular data are included). 15. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences. 16. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876530" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876530/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) and NaK genes (present work, 
<figureCitation box="[936,1018,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–16" captionStartId="97.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[294,1293,186,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-19@97.[279,1307,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="97" captionText="FIGURES 14–16: 14. Hypothesized relationships based on adult morphology in Pamphiliinae for several genera and species groups of Pamphilius (modified from Shinohara 2002b, only genera and species groups with molecular data are included). 15. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences. 16. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876530" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876530/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
), supported three different hypothetical relationships.
